                <div class="col-sm-6">
                    <h3>The atmosphere is another key focus. NASA’s instruments aboard satellites measure greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide and methane, which are driving global warming. By studying how these gases circulate in the atmosphere, NASA can predict changes in climate, helping us understand the interconnectedness between emissions, weather patterns, and climate change impacts.</h3>
                    <h3>NASA also monitors the cryosphere—the frozen regions of Earth—including glaciers, ice sheets, and sea ice. Changes in polar ice, monitored by missions such as ICESat-2, are closely linked to global sea levels. The melting of ice sheets due to warming temperatures affects ocean circulation, which in turn influences global climate systems</h3>
                    <h3>The water cycle is a critical element of Earth’s interconnectedness, and NASA’s satellites track the movement of water across the planet. By observing precipitation, evaporation, and soil moisture levels, NASA provides insights into droughts, floods, and the availability of fresh water, which are essential for human survival and ecosystem health.</h3>
